1. Converting salary into yearly salary format¶

In [9]:
job_postings1 = job_postings1[job_postings1['pay_period'].isin(['MONTHLY', 'YEARLY', 'HOURLY', 'WEEKLY']) | job_postings1['pay_period'].isnull()]

# Conversion factors to yearly salary based on American salary standards
conversion_factors = {
    'MONTHLY': 12,
    'YEARLY': 1,
    'HOURLY': 2080,  # Assuming a 40-hour work week and 52 weeks in a year
    'WEEKLY': 52
}

# Applying conversion for non-null numeric values in 'max_salary', 'med_salary', and 'min_salary' columns
for column in ['max_salary', 'med_salary', 'min_salary']:
    for period, factor in conversion_factors.items():
        mask = job_postings1['pay_period'] == period
        job_postings1.loc[mask, column] = job_postings1.loc[mask, column].apply(lambda x: x*factor if pd.notnull(x) else x)

2. Combine 3 salary columns to 1¶

In [10]:
job_postings1['annual_salary'] = np.where(job_postings1['max_salary'].notna() & job_postings1['min_salary'].notna(),
                        (job_postings1['max_salary'] + job_postings1['min_salary']) / 2,
                        np.where(job_postings1['med_salary'].notna(),
                                 job_postings1['med_salary'],
                                 np.nan))
In [11]:
job_postings1 = job_postings1[job_postings1['annual_salary'] <= 1000000]

We can use salary to fill missing job level data:

Salaries below 75000 are entry level jobs;

Salaries between 75000 and 100000 are junior level jobs;

Salaries between 100000 and 140000 are senior level jobs;

Salaries above 140000 are director level jobs

Text Pre-Processing¶

Various functions to preprocess the job description text:¶

In [40]:
# Function to remove special character "!"#$%&'()*+, -./:;<=>?@[\]^_`{|}~"
def remove_punctuation(text):
    punctuation = string.punctuation + "–"
    return re.sub(f"[{re.escape(punctuation)}]", " ", text)

# Function to remove Digits
def remove_digits(text):
    return "".join(filter(lambda char: not char.isdigit(), text))

# Function to remove urls
def remove_urls(text):
    url_pattern = r'https?://\S+|www\.\S+|\b\S+\.(com|net|org|info|edu)\b'
    return re.sub(url_pattern, '', text)

# Function to remove HTML Tag
def remove_html(text):
    html_pattern = re.compile("<.*?>")
    return html_pattern.sub(r"", text)

#Function to remove email texts
def remove_emails(text):
    return re.sub(r"\S+@\S+", "", text)

# Tokenize the description column
def tokenize_text(text):
    return word_tokenize(text)

#Function to convert the tokens into lower strings
def convert_to_lower_case(tokens):
    return [token.lower() for token in tokens]

#Function to remove single alphabets, repeat words and non-alphanumeric characters
def remove_single_alphabets(tokens):    
    # Remove single alphabets
    tokens = [token for token in tokens if len(token) > 1]
       
    return tokens

# Function to remove stop words
def remove_combined_stop_words(tokens):
    
    # Get a set of English stop words
    english_stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

    # Custom stop words
    custom_stop_words = [
        "job", "role", "position", "responsibility", "responsibilities", "duties", "duty", "ability", 'six', 'seven', 'eight', 'nine'
        "requirement", "requirements", "qualification", "qualifications", "description", 'one', 'two', 'three', 'four', 'five', 'zero'
        "descriptions", "candidate", "candidates", "applicant", "applicants", "opportunity", "low", "high", "lower", "lowest",
        "opportunities", "team", "teams", "work", "working", "employee", "employees", "largest", "higher", "highest", "basic",
        "employer", "employers", "company", "companies", "location", "locations", "american", "us", "registry", "large", "larger",
        "department", "departments", "report", "reports", "reporting", "benefit", "benefits", "technologist", "small", "smaller",
        "compensation", "salary", "experience", "experienced", "year", "years", "gender", "minimum", "maximum", "tech", "technology",
        "race", "color", "sex", "orientation", "sexual", "religion", "national", "identify", "type", "types", "hire", "must", "obtain",
        "veteran", "nation", "including", "required", "disability", "regard", "skills", "skill", "abilities", "month", "year", "fte",
    ]

    # Combine English and custom stop words
    combined_stop_words = english_stop_words.union(custom_stop_words)
    
    return [token for token in tokens if token not in combined_stop_words]

#Lemmatizer to bring the tokens to their root word
def lemmatize_tokens(tokens):
    
    # Initialize the WordNet Lemmatizer
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(token) for token in tokens]

# Function for text-preprocessing

def preprocess_text(text):
    
    #Remove urls
    text_wout_urls = remove_urls(text)
    
    #Remove html
    text_wout_html = remove_html(text_wout_urls)
    
    #Remove emails
    text_wout_email = remove_emails(text_wout_html)
    
    #Remove the punctuations
    text_wout_punc = remove_punctuation(text_wout_email)
    
    #Remove digits
    text_wout_digits = remove_digits(text_wout_punc)
    
    # Tokenize the text
    tokens = tokenize_text(text_wout_digits)
    
    # Convert tokens to lowercase
    lower_tokens = convert_to_lower_case(tokens)
    
    #Remove digits in words, single alphabets, non-alphanumeric char
    tokens_wout_salph = remove_single_alphabets(lower_tokens)

    # Expand contractions
    expanded_tokens = expand_contractions(tokens_wout_salph)

    # Remove stop words
    no_stop_words_tokens = remove_combined_stop_words(expanded_tokens)

    # Lemmatize the tokens
    lemmatized_tokens = lemmatize_tokens(no_stop_words_tokens)
    
    # Rejoin the tokens into a processed string
    processed_text = ' '.join(lemmatized_tokens)

    return processed_text

def count_skills(description, skill_bank):
  
  words = description.lower().split()
  skills = [skill for skill in words if skill in skill_bank]
  desc_skills = set(skills)
  skill_cnt = len(desc_skills)
  return skill_cnt, desc_skills

def compute_coherence_values(corpus, dictionary, k, a, b):
    
    lda_model = LdaMulticore(corpus=doc_term_matrix,
                       id2word=dictionary,
                       num_topics=k,
                       random_state=100,                  
                       passes=50,
                       alpha=a,
                       eta=b,
                       workers=workers)
    
    coherence_model_lda = CoherenceModel(model=lda_model, texts=job_postings['jd_trigrams'], dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
    
    return coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()

def tic():
    global start_time 
    start_time = time.time()

def tac():
    t_sec = round(time.time() - start_time)
    (t_min, t_sec) = divmod(t_sec,60)
    (t_hour,t_min) = divmod(t_min,60) 
    print(f'Execution time to calculate for topic {k}: {t_hour}hour:{t_min}min:{t_sec}sec'.format(t_hour,t_min,t_sec))

def get_dominant_topic(lda_model, corpus):
    # Create a mapping from numerical identifiers to letters (A, B, C, ...)
    topic_names = {i: letter for i, letter in enumerate(string.ascii_uppercase)}
    
    # Get the dominant topic for each document
    topics = [max(doc, key=lambda x: x[1])[0] for doc in lda_model[corpus]]
    
    # Map the numerical topic identifiers to names (A, B, C, ...)
    named_topics = [topic_names[topic] if topic in topic_names else 'Beyond_Z' for topic in topics]
    return named_topics

Function to extract text data from the resumes:¶

In [62]:
def text_extraction_from_pdf(pdf_path):

    # Function to extract text from a single PDF file
    def extract_text_from_pdf(pdf_path):
        with fitz.open(pdf_path) as doc:
            text = ""
            for page in doc:
                text += page.get_text()
        return text

    # Read the PDF and extract text from the provided path
    resume_text = extract_text_from_pdf(pdf_path)

    # Convert to lowercase for consistent matching
    resume_text = resume_text.lower()

    # Section headings in resume
    section_headings = [
        'experience', 'work experience', 'professional experience', 'work history',
        'professional background', 'employment history', 'education', 'academic background',
        'qualifications', 'projects', 'portfolio', 'skills', 'technical skills',
        'proficiencies', 'competencies', 'certifications', 'awards', 'honors',
        'publications', 'languages', 'volunteer work', 'extracurricular activities'
    ]

    # Regex pattern that matches the section headings
    section_headings_pattern = r'|'.join([re.escape(heading) for heading in section_headings])

    patterns = {
        'credentials': fr'(?i)\b(?:{section_headings_pattern})\b(.*?)(?=\n\b(?:{section_headings_pattern})\b)',
    }

    def extract_sections(text, patterns):
        sections = {}
        for key, pattern in patterns.items():
            # Use finditer to capture all occurrences of the pattern
            matches = list(re.finditer(pattern, text, re.DOTALL | re.IGNORECASE))
            if matches:
                sections[key] = [match.group(1).strip() for match in matches]
            else:
                print(f"No match found for the section: {key}")
        return sections

    # Extract sections
    extracted_sections = extract_sections(resume_text, patterns)

    processed_sections = {}

    # Iterate over each section in the extracted sections
    for section, content_list in extracted_sections.items():
        # Process each content in the list
        processed_content = [preprocess_text(content) for content in content_list if content]
        processed_sections[section] = processed_content

    credentials_dict = processed_sections
    # Join lists in credentials_dict with newline characters
    credentials_string = '\n\n'.join('\n'.join(contents) for contents in credentials_dict.values())
    extracted_text = preprocess_text(credentials_string)

    return extracted_text

def recommend_similar_jobs(job_title, job_postings):
    
    job_title = job_title.lower()
    
    # Filter out noise with cluster != -1
    filtered_jobs = job_postings
    
    # Find clusters that contain the job title exactly or closely
    clusters = filtered_jobs[filtered_jobs['title'].str.lower().str.contains(job_title)]['cluster'].unique()
    
    # Recommend jobs from those clusters
    similar_jobs = filtered_jobs[filtered_jobs['cluster'].isin(clusters)]
    
    # Optional: Sort by how closely the job titles match the search term
    similar_jobs['title_match'] = similar_jobs['title'].apply(lambda x: job_title in x.lower())
    similar_jobs = similar_jobs.sort_values('title_match', ascending=False).drop('title_match', axis=1)
    
    return similar_jobs[['job_id', 'title', 'company_name', 'cluster']]

2. Job Recommendation based on TF-IDF and cosine similarity:¶

In [77]:
def recommend_jobs_tcs(candidate_profile, df, desired_work_type=None, a = (1,1)):
    
    # Function to format the work type
    def format_work_type(work_type):
        # Remove non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lower case
        return re.sub(r'\W+', '', work_type).lower()

    # Filter the dataframe based on a flexible work type matching
    if desired_work_type is not None:
        desired_work_type_formatted = format_work_type(desired_work_type)
        df = df[df['formatted_work_type'].apply(format_work_type) == desired_work_type_formatted]

    # Check if there are any jobs left after filtering
    if df.empty:
        print("No jobs found matching the specified work type.")
        return pd.DataFrame()

    #Initialize TFIDF vectorizer
    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english', ngram_range = a)
    
    # Textual Similarity using TF-IDF on the filtered dataframe
    tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['processed_description'])

    # Transform the candidate's profile using the same vectorizer
    candidate_vector = vectorizer.transform([candidate_profile])

    # Compute cosine similarity between candidate's profile and job descriptions
    cosine_similarities = linear_kernel(candidate_vector, tfidf_matrix).flatten()

    # Get indices of jobs sorted by similarity
    sorted_job_indices = cosine_similarities.argsort()[::-1]

    top_job_indices = sorted_job_indices[:min(10, len(sorted_job_indices))]
    
    # Select the top similar jobs
    top_jobs = df.iloc[top_job_indices]
    
    # Add the similarity score to the DataFrame
    top_jobs['similarity_score'] = cosine_similarities[top_job_indices]
    
    # Group by title and company_name and take the first entry from each group to avoid duplicates
    top_jobs_unique = top_jobs.groupby(['title', 'company_name']).head(1)

    # Sort the unique jobs based on similarity score
    top_jobs_unique_sorted = top_jobs_unique.sort_values(by=['similarity_score'], ascending=[False])

    # Return the top unique sorted jobs
    return top_jobs_unique_sorted[['title', 'company_name', 'job_posting_url']]

3. Job Recommendation based on CountVectorizer and cosine similarity:¶

In [86]:
def recommend_jobs_ccs(candidate_profile, df, skill_bank, desired_work_type=None, a = (1, 1)):
    
    # Function to format the work type
    def format_work_type(work_type):
        # Remove non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lower case
        return re.sub(r'\W+', '', work_type).lower()

    # Filter the dataframe based on a flexible work type matching
    if desired_work_type is not None:
        desired_work_type_formatted = format_work_type(desired_work_type)
        df = df[df['formatted_work_type'].apply(format_work_type) == desired_work_type_formatted]

    # Check if there are any jobs left after filtering
    if df.empty:
        print("No jobs found matching the specified work type.")
        return pd.DataFrame()

    # Initialize the CountVectorizer
    vectorizer = CountVectorizer(ngram_range = a)

    # Textual Similarity using CountVectorizer on the filtered dataframe
    count_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['processed_description'])

    # Transform the candidate's profile using the same vectorizer
    candidate_vector = vectorizer.transform([candidate_profile])

    # Compute cosine similarity between candidate's profile and job descriptions
    cosine_similarities = cosine_similarity(candidate_vector, count_matrix).flatten()

    # Get indices of jobs sorted by cosine similarity
    sorted_job_indices_cosine = cosine_similarities.argsort()[::-1]
   
    top_job_indices = sorted_job_indices_cosine[:min(5, len(sorted_job_indices_cosine))]
    
    # Select the top similar jobs
    top_jobs = df.iloc[top_job_indices]
    
    top_jobs['similarity_score'] = cosine_similarities[top_job_indices]

    # Sort the jobs based on similarity score
    top_jobs = top_jobs.sort_values(by=['similarity_score'], ascending=False)
    
    return top_jobs[['title', 'company_name']]
